<h3 id="manage-pull-requests">Manage Pull requests</h3>
<p>Now notice how thereâ€™s a yellow, long box and at the end thereâ€™s a green box labeled â€œCompare &amp; pull requestâ€. Essentially how Github is structured is that there is a â€˜masterâ€™ branch that should be working and have the final iteration of changes. Itâ€™s the â€˜masterâ€™ branch for a reasonâ€¦ Now if you want to make some edits to your code, you would branch off of the master and make edits there. Thatâ€™s what we did before when we did â€˜git checkout -b branch1â€™. Now, if youâ€™re happy with the edits and changes youâ€™ve made to your code, you can then â€˜mergeâ€™ your branch and the master branch, leaving the master branch updated with content from said branch. This is what the â€œCompare &amp; pull requestâ€ is allowing you to do.</p>

<p>So, click on â€œCompare &amp; pull requestâ€</p>

<hr />
<p><img src="/assets/images/2020-04-28-How-to_use-Git/compare_pull1.PNG" alt="compare_pull1" /></p>

<hr />

<p>In this upper section, you can see the commit message that you wrote previously when pushing. If youâ€™re happy with the edits, click â€œCreate pull requestâ€ &gt; then â€œMerge pull requestâ€ &gt; then â€œConfirm mergeâ€. If you scroll down further, you can also see the specific changes that will be made to your files in the master branch.</p>

<hr />
<p><img src="/assets/images/2020-04-28-How-to_use-Git/compare_pull2.PNG" alt="compare_pull2" /></p>

<hr />

<p>If you also want, on the right side, thereâ€™s an option to pick either â€˜Unifiedâ€™ or â€˜Splitâ€™. The split option looks like the one below.</p>

<hr />
<p><img src="/assets/images/2020-04-28-How-to_use-Git/compare_pull3.PNG" alt="compare_pull3" /></p>

<hr />

<p>Now that you completed the merge request, go back to your repository page and under the master branch you should see your file edits/changes.</p>

